</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3266529FFBBFFAEFF0CFDECDB85FC95" pageId="5" pageNumber="330" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B8336A2FFBBFFAEFF0CFDECDB85FC95" blockId="5.[151,1437,361,784]" pageId="5" pageNumber="330">
<emphasis id="B948EAB0FFBBFFAEFF0CFDECD97AFDD9" bold="true" box="[199,315,578,604]" pageId="5" pageNumber="330">Remarks.</emphasis>
The loss of the 
<typeStatus id="54878800FFBBFFAEFE32FDECDA68FDD9" box="[505,553,578,604]" pageId="5" pageNumber="330">type</typeStatus>
(Hamburg Museum, WWII) and no other verified material makes it difficult to assess the correct position in micracidine classification. In the absence of evidence to the contrary, it is prudent to maintain taxonomic stability by the application of a diagnosis that embrace the Malagasy species related to 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D21FFBBFFAEFA43FD25DA51FD4C" authority="(Schedl, 1961)" baseAuthorityName="Schedl" baseAuthorityYear="1961" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Pseudomicracis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="madagascariensis">
<emphasis id="B948EAB0FFBBFFAEFA43FD25D920FD4D" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="330">P. madagascariensis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD4B53FFBBFFAEFEBAFD00DA46FD4C" author="Schedl, K. E." box="[369,519,686,713]" pageId="5" pageNumber="330" pagination="127 - 170" refId="ref10492" refString="Schedl, K. E. (1961) Fauna Madagascariensis, IV. 188 contribution. Institut Scientifique de Madagascar, Memoires, Series E, 12, 127 - 170." type="journal article" year="1961">Schedl, 1961</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
as did 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD4B53FFBBFFAEFDA8FD00DABAFD4C" author="Wood, S. L." box="[611,763,686,713]" pageId="5" pageNumber="330" pagination="1 - 126" refId="ref10717" refString="Wood, S. L. (1986) A reclassification of the genera of Scolytidae (Coleoptera). Great Basin Naturalist Memoirs, 10, 1 - 126." type="journal article" year="1986">Wood (1986)</bibRefCitation>
. It is apparent from studies on closely related genera in the flagellum clade that all these have a southern African and Malagasy distribution; the occurrence of a single African species in 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D21FFBBFFAEFEC7FD58D9FEFC95" authorityName="Eggers" authorityYear="1920" box="[268,447,758,784]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Pseudomicracis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B948EAB0FFBBFFAEFEC7FD58D9FEFC95" box="[268,447,758,784]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="330">Pseudomicracis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
will therefore not be evidence to the contrary.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
